gate.ac.uk)), is a novel platform and experimental apparatus for text
processing which promotes the following desirable characteristics of research:

- _Measurement._ Progress in language processing is driven by metrics
  supporting quantitative evaluation of alternative approaches. GATE automates
  metrics and has been evaluated in all the leading measurement programmes
  including MUC, TREC, ACE, DUC, Pascal, etc.
- _Repeatability._ The complexity of human language computation systems has
  made it difficult to replicate experimental data at multiple laboratories.
  GATE provides a level playing field and a networked plugin capability which
  significantly reduces the overheads and has encouraged repeatability as a
  result.
- _Longevity._ Specialists in language are not always expert in software
  engineering, which creates problems in apparatus construction and for the
  longevity of the systems that prove particular results. GATE removes most of
  the responsibility for engineering apparatus from the research community and
  makes it easier to package experimental components in a robust and
  long-lasting form.

GATE is over 15 years old and is in active use for all types of computational
task involving human language. GATE excels at text analysis of all shapes and
sizes.</api:text></api:field><api:field name="authors" type="person-list" display-name="Authors"><api:people><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="1851" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/1851"/></api:links><api:last-name>Cunningham</api:last-name><api:initials>H</api:initials><api:first-names>H</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>H</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="70" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/70"/></api:links><api:last-name>Tablan</api:last-name><api:initials>V</api:initials><api:first-names>V</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>V</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="1111" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/1111"/></api:links><api:last-name>Bontcheva</api:last-name><api:initials>K</api:initials><api:first-names>K</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>K</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="321" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/321"/></api:links><api:last-name>Roberts</api:last-name><api:initials>I</api:initials><api:first-names>I</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>I</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:last-name>Maynard</api:last-name><api:initials>D</api:initials><api:first-names>D</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>D</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:last-name>Roberts</api:last-name><api:initials>A</api:initials><api:first-names>A</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>A</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="el